    </div>
</section>

<!-- Methodology Section -->
<section class="container mb-5">
    <h2 class="section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <div class="row">
    </div>

            <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
                <div class="card-body">
                    <h5 class="card-title">Analytical Approach</h5>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Causal Model Specification:</strong> Developed a directed acyclic graph (DAG) to model assumed causal relationships</li>
                        <li><strong>Regression Analysis:</strong> Multiple regression models with carefully selected covariates to isolate causal effects</li>
                        <li><strong>Mediation Analysis:</strong> Quantified direct and indirect effects of education on health</li>
                        <li><strong>Machine Learning:</strong> Used Random Forest for feature importance and partial dependence plots</li>
                        <li><strong>Policy Simulation:</strong> Estimated potential outcomes under various intervention scenarios</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
</section>


    
    <!-- Causal Graph Visualization -->

<!-- Key Findings -->
<section class="container mb-5">
</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Key Findings</h2>
    
    <!-- Income Determinants -->
    <div class="card visualization-card mb-5">
        <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">1. Income Determinants</h4>
            <p class="card-text">Each additional year of education increases income by approximately $3,000.  This effect actually varies a great amount depending on the family background.</p>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <div class="text-center">
                        <img src="static/images/causal_inference/income_coefficients.png" alt="Income Determinants" class="img-fluid viz-img">
                        <figcaption class="text-muted mt-2">Significant coefficients in the income model showing the relative importance of different factors.</figcaption>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <div class="text-center">
                        <img src="static/images/causal_inference/education_effect_by_background.png" alt="Education Effect by Background" class="img-fluid viz-img">
                        <figcaption class="text-muted mt-2">Effect of education on income.</figcaption>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <!-- Mediation Analysis -->
    <div class="card visualization-card mb-5">
        <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">2. Mediation Analysis: Education → Income → Health</h4>
            <p class="card-text">Education affects health both directly and indirectly through income. Approximately 42% of education's total effect on health is mediated through increased income.</p>
            <div class="text-center">
                <img src="static/images/causal_inference/mediation_visualization.png" alt="Mediation Analysis" class="img-fluid viz-img" style="max-width: 700px;">
                <figcaption class="text-muted mt-2">Visual representation of the mediation analysis showing direct and indirect effects of education on health outcomes.</figcaption>
            </div>
            <div class="row mt-4">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <table class="table table-bordered">
                        <thead class="table-light">
                            <tr>
                                <th>Effect Type</th>
                                <th>Magnitude</th>
                                <th>Percentage</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Total Effect</td>
                                <td>2.45 points</td>
                                <td>100%</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Direct Effect</td>
                                <td>1.42 points</td>
                                <td>58%</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Indirect Effect (via Income)</td>
                                <td>1.03 points</td>
                                <td>42%</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <p><strong>Interpretation:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Each year of education directly increases health score by 1.42 points</li>
                        <li>Each year of education indirectly increases health score by 1.03 points through higher income</li>
                        <li>The significant mediation effect suggests that policies addressing both education and income will have the strongest impact on health outcomes</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    

<!-- Conclusions Section -->
<section class="container mb-5">
    <h2 class="section-title">Conclusions</h2>
    <div class="card border-0 shadow">
        <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="mb-3">Key Insights</h4>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Education Has Substantial Causal Effects:</strong> Each additional year of education increases income by approximately $3,000 after controlling for confounding factors.</li>
                <li><strong>Health Effects Are Both Direct and Indirect:</strong> About 42% of education's effect on health is mediated through income, while 58% is direct (possibly through knowledge, behaviors, and access).</li>
                <li><strong>Gender Wage Gap Increases with Age:</strong> The analysis revealed a significant interaction between gender and age, with the wage gap growing larger for older individuals.</li>
            </ol>
            
        </div>
    </div>
</section>



